From 461c8881f698cc8961e09421399b18684f30b392 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Jonas Jelonek <jelonek.jonas@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 26 Jun 2025 11:39:42 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 1/2] i2c: make RTL9300 I2C driver compatibles more generic

Currently, the RTL9300 I2C driver uses SoC-specific compatible strings
like 'realtek,rtl9301-i2c', 'realtek,rtl9302b-i2c'. While this might be
for a good reason, it is counter-intuitive for the usecase of defining
the I2C controllers within a generic DTSI like 'rtl930x.dtsi'. Right
now this requires more specific DTS/DTSI to adjust the compatible string
again.

This is less understandable looking at the fact that within the RTL9300
series, the different SoCs have the same I2C capabilities and use the
same register layout. Moreover, the driver currently doesn't use this
distinction for anything, and 'realtek,rtl9301-i2c' is currently used as
some kind of generic although RTL9301 are specific SoCs.

To cleanup this confusion, this adds a generic compatible string
'realtek,rtl9300-i2c' for the whole RTL9300 series. Existing compatibles
are kept for backward compatibility and to still allow SoC-specific
distinctions in the unlikely case of any differences.

The compatible 'realtek,rtl9301-i2c' is degraded to a non-generic.
Instead 'realtek,rtl9300-i2c' should be used as a generic. Since this
driver is not yet used that much, this also introduces
non-backward-compatible changes to the compatible strings and adjusts
all usages.

Signed-off-by: Jonas Jelonek <jelonek.jonas@gmail.com>

diff --git a/drivers/i2c/busses/i2c-rtl9300.c b/drivers/i2c/busses/i2c-rtl9300.c
index e064e8a4a1f0..e02a8ba40f6f 100644
--- a/drivers/i2c/busses/i2c-rtl9300.c
+++ b/drivers/i2c/busses/i2c-rtl9300.c
@@ -401,6 +401,7 @@ static int rtl9300_i2c_probe(struct platform_device *pdev)
 }
 
 static const struct of_device_id i2c_rtl9300_dt_ids[] = {
+	{ .compatible = "realtek,rtl9300-i2c" },
 	{ .compatible = "realtek,rtl9301-i2c" },
 	{ .compatible = "realtek,rtl9302b-i2c" },
 	{ .compatible = "realtek,rtl9302c-i2c" },
-- 
